Section 13(3) of the Federal Reserve Act, which permits the Federal Reserve to do emergency lending to businesses under "unusual and exigent circumstances," was passed in 1932 during the depths of the Depression. The context differed profoundly from today – for example, policymakers were concerned that in some regions with extensive bank failures, businesses might lack banking services altogether. The original 13(3) also contemplated that emergency powers could be used to lend directly to businesses, instead of simply to financial interests.
